Tiger Seed Auerbach’s Hound Partners Mulls Long-Only Fund	


					July 25, 2013

					 
                    Stephen Taub
				

					The New York-based manager would join other Tiger-affiliated managers including Stephen Mandel Jr., O. Andreas Halvorsen and Lee Ainslie in launching a long-only product to run alongside his firm’s hedge funds.
				



Jonathan Auerbach’s New York–based
    hedge fund firm Hound Partners may become the latest
    Tiger-affiliated manager to launch a long-only fund.
In a letter dated July 18, Auerbach says such a vehicle has
    been "under strong consideration" for a year and a half after
    he was inspired by a "very positive commentary of another Tiger
    Cub who Julian [Robertson] had over for lunch." (Tiger Cubs are
    managers who worked for Robertson’s famed hedge
    fund firm, Tiger Management. Auerbach is what is known as a
    Tiger Seed, having launched with money from Robertson.)
Auerbach did not name the Cub. He also said a few investors
    have been asking for a long-only product. "We are actively
    debating the pros and cons of offering such a vehicle and would
    love your feedback," Auerbach urged investors.
We reported earlier this year that Tiger Cub
    Philippe Laffont’s Coatue Management filed plans
    with the Securities and Exchange Commission to launch a
    long-only fund. Other Cubs who manage successful long-only
    funds include Stephen Mandel Jr. of Lone Pine Capital, O.
    Andreas Halvorsen of Viking Global Investors and Lee Ainslie of
    Maverick Capital.
Auerbach co-founded his firm with Scott McLellan in 2004. In
    2007, McLellan launched Marble Arch Partners with Tiger alum
    Timothy Jenkins. Auerbach previously served as a senior analyst
    at Ziff Brothers Investments.
In his letter, Auerbach said he will structure his long-only
    fund differently from those offered by the Cubs, whose long
    fund portfolios mostly mimic the long book in their hedge
    funds. His fund would be more concentrated and have a longer
    holding period and would focus on companies that can compound
    for many years. The fund would also "possibly focus on
    tax-efficiency," he said in the letter.
"In a world where tax rates are rising, recent performance
    from alternatives has been mediocre (and not particularly
    tax-efficient), the better long-short funds are capacity
    constrained (largely on the short side), and the traditional
    long-only business has suffered a decade-long brain drain, I
    have felt a clear need for this type of investment vehicle in
    my conversations with investors," Auerbach explained.
He is sensitive to the notion that earlier major launches of
    long-only funds "by the pioneers of long-only funds managed by
    long-short managers" occurred at tops of markets. Auerbach
    insists he is taking a longer view. He also pledged that he and
    his entire senior team will "make a substantial personal
    investment."
The hedge fund manager also told clients he will not raise
    "significant capital" in the long-short fund in 2014, other
    than to replace redemptions, which he said have been at very
    low levels. This is not surprising given that his hedge fund,
    Hound Partners, posted an impressive 14.71 percent net return
    in the first half of this year, while the long portfolio gained
    20.83 percent gross of fees. In 2012 it was up 18.59 percent
    net, while the long portfolio was up 18.55 percent gross.
In his July letter, Auerbach sounded almost giddy, telling
    investors, "After several years of getting off to a strong
    start and temporarily fading into mid-year, we are pleased to
    have held on to our gains and remain enthusiastic about our
    portfolio." He pointed out that he runs a concentrated
    portfolio, with three stocks each accounting for 10 percent of
    assets, which are about $1.8 billion according to sources.
The biggest winner was FleetCor Technologies, which provides
    specialized payment products and services to businesses,
    commercial fleets and energy companies. It surged 50 percent in
    the first half of the year. Auerbach said in the letter he
    continues to hold a sizable position.
He trimmed his position in the warrants of energy company
    Kinder Morgan, mostly due to strong performance, and said he
    expanded his position in Valeant Pharmaceuticals International
    prior to its announcement that it would acquire Bausch &
    Lomb. On the other hand, he acknowledged losing money on Golar
    LNG, a London-based liquefied natural gas shipping company.






